# 🤝 Multi-Agent Setup

How to run multiple OpenClaw agents on a single gateway — and how to wire them up to coordinate with each other.

---

## When to add a second agent

Add a new agent when:
- A domain is complex enough to deserve its own identity and procedures
- You want to separate concerns cleanly (health vs. home ops vs. finances)
- A task runs on a different schedule than your primary agent
- You want one agent's output to feed another's input

Do not add a new agent just because you have more tasks. Start with one agent and extend it until the complexity genuinely justifies a split.

---

## The single gateway model

A gateway is how agents hand off state. OpenClaw uses a file-based gateway — agents write outputs to files or Google Docs, and other agents read them on their next session.

```
Sage (Saturday EOD)
  └─► writes health guidelines → Google Doc

Heidi (Sunday morning)
  └─► reads Google Doc
  └─► builds meal plan
  └─► posts to Telegram

Frank (3 AM nightly)
  └─► reads Heidi workspace files
  └─► distills context
  └─► starts fresh Heidi session
```

No agent talks directly to another agent in real time. They communicate through shared state. This is simpler, cheaper, and more reliable than real-time agent-to-agent communication.

